WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:15.680
Hi, I'm Caitlin Hudon. I'm here to talk about eight years of making data science mistakes.

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:21.440
So just a quick about me, I am lead data scientist at Online MedEd. That's a startup here in

00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:27.480
Austin. Co-organizer of Our Ladies Austin, really big fan of that community, also into

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:36.400
traveling, hiking, tacos. Yay! I blog at CaitlinHudon.com. I tweet at Beyond a Posey.

00:00:36.400 --> 00:00:41.279
And I also have a hashtag, DSLearnings, where I track some of the things that I've been

00:00:41.279 --> 00:00:47.520
learning and try to share that with the community. So before we get into all the mistakes I've

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:51.080
made, let's talk a little bit about why we should share our mistakes. One thing that's

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:56.639
really important to me is transparency. I think if we were all a little bit more transparent,

00:00:56.639 --> 00:01:01.040
it would make our community better. I think it would help fend off a little bit of imposter

00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:06.199
syndrome if we admitted things that we don't know alongside things that we do. I also think

00:01:06.199 --> 00:01:10.160
it's helpful for newcomers to see that other people have faced the same issues that they're

00:01:10.160 --> 00:01:15.800
seeing. To help other people, so I've learned a ton from other people's mistakes when I'm

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:19.959
implementing new products, that sort of thing. It's great to get advice. So I hope that you

00:01:19.959 --> 00:01:25.360
learn something today. Also growth. So I am the sum of all of the mistakes that I've made

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:30.000
up to this point. Mistakes count as experience. It's how you gain experience. It's how you

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:36.879
become the analyst or the person that you eventually are. I'm going to talk about two

00:01:36.879 --> 00:01:44.120
types of mistakes mainly today. So one is technical mistakes. The other is communication

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:51.279
mistakes. I think that people tend to make a lot more technical mistakes in the beginning.

00:01:51.279 --> 00:01:57.559
And over time, you maybe make fewer communication mistakes, but I think that fundamentally,

00:01:57.559 --> 00:02:01.680
communication is harder than tech. So we'll cover a little bit of both of these. And we'll

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:07.400
cover four sort of mistake zones. So we're going to start at the beginning of my career.

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:12.399
And I was working as a statistical analyst. It was my job to build predictive models for

00:02:12.399 --> 00:02:19.399
nonprofits, higher education, small businesses, that sort of thing. And I was the first hire

00:02:19.399 --> 00:02:24.520
at this company. And so before me, the CEO had built all of the models. So no pressure

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:29.240
there. So this is me when I built my first model.

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:33.639
I was super pumped about it, very confident. I thought I was good to go. I had set up a

00:02:33.639 --> 00:02:39.199
meeting to present it to a client. This was after a lot of training. I didn't start off

00:02:39.199 --> 00:02:44.080
building models. I did a lot of training first. So I had to sit down with my CEO so that he

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:53.000
could review my work. I was ready to go. I thought it was good. Completely bombed.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.479
And so he found a couple of issues with the model that I built. I was trying to predict

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:03.119
enrollment. So based on students who had been accepted at a college, I was going to predict

00:03:03.119 --> 00:03:08.639
like who would actually accept that offer and show up in the fall.

00:03:08.639 --> 00:03:14.600
In doing so, I had included two problematic variables in my model. One was deposit. So

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:19.000
if you've ever gone to a college, before you can do that, you have to make a deposit. That's

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:22.919
like a pretty much proxy for enrollment. They have a thing called summer melt, so it's not

00:03:22.919 --> 00:03:27.839
exactly the same. But highly problematic to have that in a model.

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:33.960
The other thing was a variable called campus visit. So any training data that we have,

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:39.800
we get after the fact. And so we didn't have enough information to actually use this variable.

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:44.139
We had campus visit but no date. Some people visit campus in the fall while they're looking

00:03:44.139 --> 00:03:48.919
at schools. Some people go to like an accepted student's day. And we had no way of knowing

00:03:48.919 --> 00:03:52.320
whether these people fell into the former category or the latter.

00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:58.479
So those were two variables that I couldn't use. I spent about four years at this company

00:03:58.479 --> 00:04:07.479
building models. And during that time I made a couple of mistakes. Those mistakes became

00:04:07.479 --> 00:04:14.080
things that I knew to look for when I was building models. So I worked in the same areas.

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:17.760
And those models started to look similar. I started to get really good at building those

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:22.119
types of models, looking for those types of mistakes.

00:04:22.119 --> 00:04:29.239
So my DS learning is to look for the usual suspects. So as you start modeling in a particular

00:04:29.239 --> 00:04:34.839
domain, you'll start to see the same problems crop up over and over again in your data.

00:04:34.839 --> 00:04:39.359
For me, a lot of that was like understanding the data source and data collection. I think

00:04:39.359 --> 00:04:43.679
that's really important. The assumptions that we're making, any filters we're adding, missing

00:04:43.679 --> 00:04:47.600
values, and then understanding the goals of the model, when it was supposed to be implemented,

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:50.640
who it was supposed to impact, that sort of thing.

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:54.480
So we're going to fast forward to mistake zone number two. This is communicating with

00:04:54.480 --> 00:05:01.679
devs. So I moved to Austin, started a new role. And as part of that role, we were working

00:05:01.679 --> 00:05:07.359
on this really cool feature in a product that was marketed to dentists, dental offices.

00:05:07.359 --> 00:05:12.600
So when you cancel an appointment, there is a hole in the calendar. And we wanted to be

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:16.399
able to fill that hole with the person who would be most likely to take a last minute

00:05:16.399 --> 00:05:23.799
appointment. I was doing R&D for that algorithm. So I was looking at patterns in appointment

00:05:23.799 --> 00:05:27.359
history. Like, do people tend to always make their appointments in the morning or on the

00:05:27.359 --> 00:05:32.119
same day of the week? And so we would ask one question that would beget more questions.

00:05:32.119 --> 00:05:39.359
And we went down the rabbit hole. One thing that we found is after we did our first analysis,

00:05:39.359 --> 00:05:45.720
we realized that there was an issue with time zones. Nobody had noticed it until we

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:50.519
were having a conversation about the data a little while later.

00:05:50.519 --> 00:05:56.519
And so we did sort of a postmortem. And we figured out there were three reasons for that.

00:05:56.519 --> 00:06:00.920
One is that most of the data that I worked with wasn't time specific. It wasn't, like,

00:06:00.920 --> 00:06:05.119
minute and second specific. It was more day specific. So I think everyone has to get bit

00:06:05.119 --> 00:06:11.760
by time zones once, and then you know. Another was the way that we set up our analysis

00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:17.200
hid some errors. So we decided to look at a.m. and p.m. appointments. We didn't count

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:20.760
the number that were happening per hour. If we did, we probably would have noticed this

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:24.000
a lot sooner. The other issue was that we had a lack of

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:29.320
shared resources explaining what the data was. So any time I had a question, I had to

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:35.119
bug a dev, ask them for their explanation. I got an oral history of data, which is never

00:06:35.119 --> 00:06:40.119
good. And as people left the company, they took some of that institutional knowledge

00:06:40.119 --> 00:06:46.480
with them. It was really not fun. Eventually, we got the fill-in model to a

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:50.959
good place, and we were ready to start A.B. testing it. And so this was the first time

00:06:50.959 --> 00:06:55.720
that these devs had worked on A.B. testing. So we were doing a lot of communication. We

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:59.679
were getting everything set up. We were really excited. And when we got the results in and

00:06:59.679 --> 00:07:07.880
we started to talk about what we'd done, we realized that we ran an A.A. test.

00:07:07.880 --> 00:07:15.720
So we were trying to test different versions of the algorithm with our, like, high users,

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:20.040
and we actually had applied the new algorithm to everyone who was a high user, and all of

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:25.359
the people who didn't really use it very much had the old algorithm. So that didn't work.

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:29.679
We had to discuss it. We had to go back. It was kind of a waste of time and resources.

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:34.880
Eventually, we were able to do kind of a pre-post, so we sort of saved it, but it was a big learning

00:07:34.880 --> 00:07:41.679
experience about working with devs for me. So a few things there. Being willing to teach

00:07:41.679 --> 00:07:46.359
and to learn, and doing so very respectfully. I've worked in jobs where people have worked

00:07:46.359 --> 00:07:50.079
with a lot of data scientists. I've worked in jobs where people have never worked with

00:07:50.079 --> 00:07:53.320
a data scientist before, and so you really have to work with people and find a middle

00:07:53.320 --> 00:07:57.440
ground. Another piece was just don't play telephone.

00:07:57.440 --> 00:08:02.480
So some of the people who were actually implementing the A.B. test weren't in the important meetings

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:07.160
up front. They were just asked to sort of do the work. They didn't have the full understanding,

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:12.880
and that was borne out in the results. Another is avoiding jargon for clarity. So I've found

00:08:12.880 --> 00:08:17.279
that computer scientists tend to use different jargon. Sometimes they'll say things like

00:08:17.279 --> 00:08:22.679
data models. That means something very different than what a model means to me. And so making

00:08:22.679 --> 00:08:26.000
sure that we're being very clear about what we mean and we're actually speaking the same

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:29.600
language has been really important. The other thing is just keeping in mind that we're all

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:35.799
on the same team. We all have the same goals. We're all working towards the same thing.

00:08:35.799 --> 00:08:41.400
So the third mistake zone, communicating with business stakeholders. The next thing that

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:46.679
I was tasked to do was to figure out the impact of this new feature. So when we rolled out

00:08:46.679 --> 00:08:52.059
that feature, we expected it to have an impact on sales. We thought that we would be able

00:08:52.059 --> 00:08:56.659
to track how many more sales we sold after we'd rolled out the feature. It would be a

00:08:56.659 --> 00:09:02.900
really easy analysis. We were really excited about it. In talking with the team, we realized

00:09:02.900 --> 00:09:07.739
the way we would tell the difference is the scripts change, like a sales script changes

00:09:07.739 --> 00:09:12.619
when a new feature gets rolled out. We rolled out three features at the same time and updated

00:09:12.619 --> 00:09:19.780
them all in the script. So we couldn't actually attribute any growth to a single feature.

00:09:19.780 --> 00:09:25.840
So we went on a data adventure and I started talking to different groups of the business

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:30.840
to see what data they had that we could use to try to prove that the work that we'd done

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:39.500
had some value. When I did that, I encountered a lot of artisanal data, a lot of handcrafted,

00:09:39.500 --> 00:09:46.080
very lovingly tended to spreadsheets, which were great. They meant that this analysis

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:50.500
was not reproducible. At this point, the business teams were familiar with the types

00:09:50.500 --> 00:09:56.059
of reproducible analyses we could do. So we were running like markdown reports for A-B

00:09:56.059 --> 00:10:00.820
tests, that sort of thing. They'd seen those outputs. They wanted that output to look every

00:10:00.820 --> 00:10:08.820
month and see what the impact had been. So this was problematic. I thought a little bit

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:13.539
about how to solve this. So what's the best way for me to communicate the value of this

00:10:13.539 --> 00:10:18.159
data? Some of the data was actually really valuable. Some of it was awful. It was things

00:10:18.159 --> 00:10:23.440
that I would never want people to make decisions on, but they had also asked for it. So a secret

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:28.520
about me is I was also an English major. I really like English lit language, that sort

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:33.659
of thing. And this is something I picked up in those studies. So the rhetorical triangle

00:10:33.659 --> 00:10:39.960
is a way of framing an argument. And so it consists of three parts. The speaker, that's

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:43.599
you, all the credentials, all the background that you bring along with you, also the way

00:10:43.599 --> 00:10:48.080
that people see you. That's really important. So having sort of some awareness of how people

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:54.119
see analytics and you within an organization. The next part is the audience. So what is

00:10:54.119 --> 00:10:58.719
the audience like? Are they technical? Are they non-technical? Have they been informed

00:10:58.719 --> 00:11:03.640
of all of the ins and outs of this problem? Are they just there to make decisions as part

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:07.640
of a larger meeting? Getting some idea of who you're talking to will help you to frame

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:12.039
your argument. And then the final piece is the context. Are you delivering good news

00:11:12.039 --> 00:11:16.599
or bad news? The things that you're asking for, are they things that people can help

00:11:16.599 --> 00:11:21.359
with? Will they understand the kind of problems that you have? So putting all of this together

00:11:21.359 --> 00:11:25.119
has been really helpful for me whenever I'm talking to people who are more on the business

00:11:25.119 --> 00:11:29.440
side of things to figure out ways that I can help them and analyses can help them and we

00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:36.440
can work together. What I came up with for this particular exercise was a set of metametrics.

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:41.880
And so at the bottom of every slide I made sort of like a stoplight thing that told you

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:46.520
if the data was good, if it was trustworthy, if it was a repeatable analysis. And they

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:52.000
got this. They totally understood it. It was awesome. One of the things I found is, for

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:57.119
example, we go to trade shows and the way that we were tracking trade show data was

00:11:57.119 --> 00:12:01.159
we were hoping that a rep would tell the manager and then that the manager would remember to

00:12:01.159 --> 00:12:06.719
write down that a sale was the result of this feature. That data was horrible. It was reds

00:12:06.719 --> 00:12:10.719
all the way across. But then they knew that. And so if we wanted to invest in that data,

00:12:10.719 --> 00:12:14.799
if we wanted to start analyzing, they started to understand why we needed to put some money

00:12:14.799 --> 00:12:20.640
and some time into collecting the data and doing so in a good way. So a few learnings

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:26.119
there. Getting stakeholders involved early is really helpful to get everyone on the same

00:12:26.119 --> 00:12:30.919
page as you're working through these projects and making sure that you understand the business

00:12:30.919 --> 00:12:35.919
problem as well. So one thing that's really bad and I have done before is solving the

00:12:35.919 --> 00:12:40.880
wrong business problem or realizing at the end of an analysis that your model solves

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:47.000
the wrong business problem. A sort of funny example of that is that my first job, we were

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:53.039
building a model to predict who would be a major giver. And so that's usually or a sorry,

00:12:53.039 --> 00:12:56.919
like a bequeath. And so that's usually if someone passes away, they give a large gift

00:12:56.919 --> 00:13:01.159
to the university or to a museum or that sort of thing. We actually figured out that our

00:13:01.159 --> 00:13:06.799
model was predicting death rather than the gift that would come after. And so that was

00:13:06.799 --> 00:13:12.760
really bad. So it's just like translating the data and the business problem. That's

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:16.559
actually a really tricky thing. And so it's really helpful to talk to the business stakeholders

00:13:16.559 --> 00:13:23.000
to make sure that you're doing it right. Framing analysis in a way that makes sense. So I might

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.080
be thinking of things in terms of what they look like in the database. Those things might

00:13:27.080 --> 00:13:31.440
have totally different colloquial names around the business. And so it's really important

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:37.080
that I'm using the terminology that other people are using throughout the business.

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:41.799
Another thing that I personally am working on, and even after years of making mistakes,

00:13:41.799 --> 00:13:45.719
I still do this all the time. A lot of times you're in a meeting and people just want to

00:13:45.719 --> 00:13:51.880
know like who was in your data set, how many people was it and what did they do? I get

00:13:51.880 --> 00:13:55.760
so wrapped up in the details of my analysis and like all the things I want to tell them

00:13:55.760 --> 00:14:00.359
that I will often forget like, oh yeah, it was 600 people that I looked at. And so I

00:14:00.359 --> 00:14:07.239
tend to write those things down. Inevitably, those always come up. So making sure that

00:14:07.239 --> 00:14:12.280
you know the basic facts is really helpful. Another thing is knowing where they get their

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:18.080
data. So I've worked at companies where the BI system is different than the data that

00:14:18.080 --> 00:14:22.799
the analysts work with, like data analysts or devs or that sort of thing. That can be

00:14:22.799 --> 00:14:28.080
really problematic. So if you have people in the C-suite or stakeholders who are looking

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:35.640
at reports coming out of a system that you don't use, your numbers are not going to match.

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:42.440
And so understanding where they get their data, perfect. And how you can explain why

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:48.239
your data might be different is really important if you want to get everyone on the same page.

00:14:48.239 --> 00:14:56.479
One last problem that we'll talk about is infrastructure and team. So one of the roles

00:14:56.479 --> 00:15:04.919
that I took on was to work on the algorithm. So we had a company that a large portion of

00:15:04.919 --> 00:15:10.400
their business ran on this single set of machine learning algorithms that were in production.

00:15:10.400 --> 00:15:14.200
The fact that we refer to it as the algorithm should tell you sort of everything you need

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:19.039
to know about what the rest of the business understood about how this all worked. So we

00:15:19.039 --> 00:15:24.039
had a couple of data scientists leave at the same time. One of them was lucky enough to

00:15:24.039 --> 00:15:28.479
sit down with us and spend a whole week teaching us how the algorithm worked, the ins and outs,

00:15:28.479 --> 00:15:33.760
that sort of thing. When it came time for us to pick up the algorithm and just continue

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:40.960
to work with it, it was super scary. We did not have the documentation that we actually

00:15:40.960 --> 00:15:46.840
needed to be able to understand the algorithm, like inside out. So we had to spend a ton

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:51.880
of time trying to engineer the code, figure out where these things came from, and then

00:15:51.880 --> 00:15:57.880
explain it to other people. So one of the things that we did is wrote up some pseudocode.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:16:01.760
And I've been doing this ever since for anything that's related to machine learning or that

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:06.640
might be a little bit tougher for people to understand. So it's taking the ideas, like

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:11.159
the inputs, the outputs, the business problem you're trying to solve, and putting them into

00:16:11.159 --> 00:16:16.679
plain English. And these documents can live close to the code or separately from the code.

00:16:16.679 --> 00:16:21.400
I've even written pseudocode documents for different audiences. So one for engineers

00:16:21.400 --> 00:16:25.679
who understand the databases I'm talking about, that sort of thing, and then one for business

00:16:25.679 --> 00:16:30.159
people who need to understand the basics of the algorithm, sort of what it's doing to

00:16:30.159 --> 00:16:36.159
be able to explain it in a business context. So some learnings around infrastructure and

00:16:36.159 --> 00:16:41.760
team. I can't stress documentation enough. I've written a little bit about data dictionaries

00:16:41.760 --> 00:16:46.799
and SQL query libraries. Those have been really helpful, especially for making sure that you're

00:16:46.799 --> 00:16:52.599
not duplicating work. If you are working with different queries to find the number of active

00:16:52.599 --> 00:16:57.400
clients, for example, that should be a really simple problem. It's amazing how many times

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:02.119
I've seen this done differently by different people in the same organization. So doing

00:17:02.119 --> 00:17:05.439
things like code reviews can help you with that, making sure that everyone is on the

00:17:05.439 --> 00:17:09.760
same page. If they know the ins and outs of certain systems, that those are being communicated

00:17:09.760 --> 00:17:16.400
to the whole team. Another thing is core team meetings. So when I first started working

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:21.160
at one particular job, our analysis team was a little bit siloed, and then we started working

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:25.400
with more and more teams. One of the best things we ever did was get into these core

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:30.359
team meetings. So it was business stakeholders. We would have, like, someone from marketing,

00:17:30.359 --> 00:17:35.520
a head of product, someone from engineering, someone from data, someone from customer service.

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:40.319
All of those people, the heads of state of a single product, would come together once

00:17:40.319 --> 00:17:44.319
a week just for an hour over lunch and just kind of talk about the product, things that

00:17:44.319 --> 00:17:48.319
were coming out. But it was great, because we always had the most up-to-date information

00:17:48.319 --> 00:17:53.719
about what was going on, any issues that other teams were seeing, especially for data analysis.

00:17:53.719 --> 00:17:59.000
That context is key. It's really crucial to be able to do the right kinds of analysis.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:04.599
And then pseudocode. Pseudocode helps everyone. It's really helpful documentation to have.

00:18:04.599 --> 00:18:10.520
So I promised a little bit of advice. I have just one slide. So aspiring data scientists,

00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:15.400
learn SQL. Communication is a technical skill. It's every bit as hard as anything else that's

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:19.560
technical. Start a blog. I think Dave Robinson's going to talk a little bit more about that

00:18:19.560 --> 00:18:24.699
later on, but I love that advice. Teach others. You learn concepts more deeply when you teach

00:18:24.699 --> 00:18:30.140
them yourself. Don't worry about learning everything at first. Find your community.

00:18:30.140 --> 00:18:34.660
Community is really helpful for helping to learn. Stay curious. Have fun. Don't be afraid

00:18:34.660 --> 00:18:39.660
to use Google. And remember that everybody is winging it. Thanks.

